00:26:54.450 --> 00:26:57.120
Very good try.

00:26:57.120 --> 00:26:59.400
What essentially,
happens is that--

00:26:59.400 --> 00:27:00.580
OK, I can say, oh!

00:27:00.580 --> 00:27:05.280
Each electron are bothered
by many, many photons.

00:27:05.280 --> 00:27:08.160
So those are disturbed.

00:27:08.160 --> 00:27:15.480
Therefore, it has to look like
experimental result number two.

00:27:15.480 --> 00:27:18.360
The answer may surprise you.

00:27:18.360 --> 00:27:22.290
The answer is that,
if I have the limit

00:27:22.290 --> 00:27:28.370
lambda goes to
infinity, mu goes to 0,

00:27:28.370 --> 00:27:32.170
what is going to happen
is that, no matter how

00:27:32.170 --> 00:27:37.330
high frequency of
photon emission I have,

00:27:37.330 --> 00:27:44.700
I am going to get the result
of experimental number one.

00:27:44.700 --> 00:27:46.651
Why is that?

00:27:46.651 --> 00:27:51.190
Now, this is because
when the wavelengths

00:27:51.190 --> 00:27:55.840
of the electromagnetic
wave or the photon is going

00:27:55.840 --> 00:28:07.370
to infinity, that means you
cannot resolve which slit,

00:28:07.370 --> 00:28:10.780
actually, the
electron goes through.

00:28:10.780 --> 00:28:15.790
Because if I draw
the wavelengths here,

00:28:15.790 --> 00:28:17.770
it's going to be like this.

00:28:17.770 --> 00:28:22.450
If you observe some
kind of scattered light

00:28:22.450 --> 00:28:31.190
from the electron, it
could come from both slits,

00:28:31.190 --> 00:28:33.620
because the wavelength
is too long.

00:28:33.620 --> 00:28:35.780
So if you go to
infinity, then it's

00:28:35.780 --> 00:28:39.640
like you have a constant
electric field there.

00:28:39.640 --> 00:28:41.690
It doesn't really
actually help you

00:28:41.690 --> 00:28:45.480
to identify which slit
the electron actually

00:28:45.480 --> 00:28:47.150
passed through.

00:28:47.150 --> 00:28:52.490
So therefore, the interference
pattern reappears.

00:28:52.490 --> 00:28:58.430
So this is really crazy thing,
if you look at all these four

00:28:58.430 --> 00:29:01.870
experimental results.

00:29:01.870 --> 00:29:07.090
The conclusion from these
four imaginary experiments

00:29:07.090 --> 00:29:11.830
is that it is not
yet possible to tell

00:29:11.830 --> 00:29:17.320
the position of the electron
and also, at the same time,

00:29:17.320 --> 00:29:20.830
do not disturb it.

00:29:20.830 --> 00:29:26.470
If you were able to tell the
position of the electron,

00:29:26.470 --> 00:29:29.950
then there would be no
interference pattern.

00:29:29.950 --> 00:29:33.700
On the other hand, if
your experimental set-up

00:29:33.700 --> 00:29:38.810
have no ability at all to
tell if the electron's coming

00:29:38.810 --> 00:29:42.550
from slit number one
compared to slit number two,

00:29:42.550 --> 00:29:49.310
then you are going to
get interference pattern.

00:29:49.310 --> 00:29:53.470
There's another thing which I
would like to make connection

00:29:53.470 --> 00:29:57.490
to the Uncertainty Principle,
which we actually learn

00:29:57.490 --> 00:30:01.210
from waves and vibrations.

00:30:01.210 --> 00:30:12.170
So we have learned that
Heisenberg's Uncertainty

00:30:12.170 --> 00:30:12.860
Principle--

00:30:21.100 --> 00:30:23.420
this is essentially
purity coming

00:30:23.420 --> 00:30:28.760
from the property of the
wave, if you actually

00:30:28.760 --> 00:30:31.700
remember the deviation
which we have

00:30:31.700 --> 00:30:33.830
done in the previous lecture.

00:30:33.830 --> 00:30:38.690
So what is this uncertainty
principle telling us?

00:30:38.690 --> 00:30:44.595
Is that the standard
deviation of the position

00:30:44.595 --> 00:30:50.840
times the standard
deviation of the momentum

00:30:50.840 --> 00:30:57.560
is going to be greater or equal
to h bar over 2 some constant.

00:30:57.560 --> 00:31:00.710
And how do we actually
understand this

00:31:00.710 --> 00:31:05.430
from the electron experiment.

00:31:05.430 --> 00:31:10.220
That is actually highly related
to the single-slit experiment

00:31:10.220 --> 00:31:11.810
with electrons.

00:31:11.810 --> 00:31:17.810
So what we could do now is
to have a fifth experiment.

00:31:17.810 --> 00:31:21.470
I have electron source here.

00:31:21.470 --> 00:31:25.820
And I have a single slit.

00:31:25.820 --> 00:31:32.000
And the width of the
slit is capital D.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:35.780
And we were wondering,
what is going to happen?

00:31:35.780 --> 00:31:39.250
What will be recorded
by the smoke detector

00:31:39.250 --> 00:31:40.880
in the right-hand side?

00:31:40.880 --> 00:31:43.610
And by now, it should
not surprise you

00:31:43.610 --> 00:31:49.250
that this would give you some
kind of diffraction pattern,

00:31:49.250 --> 00:31:51.990
which you say should be very
similar to what we actually

00:31:51.990 --> 00:31:56.740
observe with laser experiments.

00:31:56.740 --> 00:31:58.390
So you can see that.

00:31:58.390 --> 00:32:02.590
The electron-- the momentum--

00:32:02.590 --> 00:32:06.950
now, I would like to actually
define my coordinate system.

00:32:06.950 --> 00:32:14.050
The vertical direction, pointing
upward, is my x direction.

00:32:14.050 --> 00:32:19.060
So now, take a look at
this experimental result.

00:32:19.060 --> 00:32:23.530
So what this is actually
telling us is the following.

00:32:23.530 --> 00:32:28.030
We know the position
of the electron

00:32:28.030 --> 00:32:35.870
to a accuracy of the
width of this slit, which

00:32:35.870 --> 00:32:39.700
is D. So that is
actually telling you

00:32:39.700 --> 00:32:49.300
about the uncertainty over the
position in the x direction.

00:32:49.300 --> 00:32:53.710
Now, this electron goes through.

00:32:53.710 --> 00:32:58.910
And they actually
hit the screen.

00:32:58.910 --> 00:33:06.070
And each electron is
having a single path.

00:33:06.070 --> 00:33:11.770
If I look at one of the paths,
the upper one, what I'm getting

00:33:11.770 --> 00:33:17.496
is that there must be a
momentum quintessentially

00:33:17.496 --> 00:33:22.820
in the x direction, when
this electronic goes

00:33:22.820 --> 00:33:28.440
through the slit
and hits the screen.

00:33:32.060 --> 00:33:35.180
One interesting thing we
learned from the deviation

00:33:35.180 --> 00:33:40.790
from last time is that, if I
just look at the slide here--

00:33:40.790 --> 00:33:43.910
if I look at the
left-hand side slide--

00:33:43.910 --> 00:33:49.150
if I have a very small slit--

00:33:49.150 --> 00:33:53.180
D is small-- what does
that correspond to?

00:33:53.180 --> 00:34:01.820
That corresponds to delta x
goes to very small value case.

00:34:01.820 --> 00:34:04.250
We have a small delta x value.

00:34:04.250 --> 00:34:08.360
You are really sure
where is the electron

00:34:08.360 --> 00:34:15.940
at some instant of time, when it
passed through the experiment.

00:34:15.940 --> 00:34:17.179
Then what is going to happen?

00:34:17.179 --> 00:34:19.429
If you look at the
right-hand side,

00:34:19.429 --> 00:34:25.810
the distribution on the screen,
you have a wide distribution.

00:34:25.810 --> 00:34:29.570
The central maximum
peak will be very wide.

00:34:29.570 --> 00:34:30.830
So what does that mean?

00:34:30.830 --> 00:34:34.250
That means you have
a wide distribution

00:34:34.250 --> 00:34:37.957
of momentum in the x direction.

00:34:40.889 --> 00:34:45.759
Therefore, that
will give you that

00:34:45.759 --> 00:34:48.860
is actually consistent with what
we've actually written here,

00:34:48.860 --> 00:34:50.460
Heisenberg's Principle.

00:34:50.460 --> 00:34:55.239
Delta x times delta p will be
greater or equal to some value.

00:34:55.239 --> 00:35:01.410
On the other hand, if I
increase the width of the slit,

00:35:01.410 --> 00:35:03.735
the D is now large.

00:35:03.735 --> 00:35:08.460
As you are making a D larger
and larger, what is happening

00:35:08.460 --> 00:35:13.550
is that the central
peak, the width,

00:35:13.550 --> 00:35:18.120
is actually going to be
narrower and narrower.

00:35:18.120 --> 00:35:20.130
Now, this is actually
also consistent with what

00:35:20.130 --> 00:35:23.250
we have learned from
Heisenberg's Uncertainty

00:35:23.250 --> 00:35:24.030
Principle.

00:35:24.030 --> 00:35:29.990
When delta x become even larger,
then the uncertainty or, say,

00:35:29.990 --> 00:35:35.320
the distribution of the
momentum in the x direction,

00:35:35.320 --> 00:35:38.310
becomes smaller.

00:35:38.310 --> 00:35:41.940
So now, we actually also
understand a little bit more

00:35:41.940 --> 00:35:46.200
about what the single
diffraction actually means.

00:35:46.200 --> 00:35:51.720
And this issue is really closely
connected to the Uncertainty

00:35:51.720 --> 00:35:55.500
Principle Heisenberg
actually proposed.

00:35:55.500 --> 00:35:58.530
And if we use the
mathematics which

00:35:58.530 --> 00:36:01.780
we learned from last
time, the C function

00:36:01.780 --> 00:36:06.060
is going to be proportional
to integration from minus D

00:36:06.060 --> 00:36:09.150
over 2 to D over 2.

00:36:09.150 --> 00:36:15.990
dx exponential as ikx times x.

00:36:15.990 --> 00:36:19.870
And if I have D
goes to infinity,

00:36:19.870 --> 00:36:24.240
which means that you have
an infinitely wide slit--

00:36:24.240 --> 00:36:28.530
based on the formula which
we have derived last time--

00:36:28.530 --> 00:36:34.680
basically, we will see that C
function is a function of kx.

00:36:34.680 --> 00:36:37.380
It's going to become
a delta function.

00:36:41.250 --> 00:36:47.270
And this delta
function is delta kx.

00:36:47.270 --> 00:36:51.720
So that means, if you
have absolutely no idea

00:36:51.720 --> 00:36:56.670
about the position
of the electron,

00:36:56.670 --> 00:37:03.950
you are going to get very, very
precise information about--

00:37:03.950 --> 00:37:07.200
the momentum in the x
direction is actually

00:37:07.200 --> 00:37:10.620
going to be equal to 0.

00:37:10.620 --> 00:37:12.160
Because it's a delta function.

00:37:12.160 --> 00:37:19.820
It's only nonzero at kx, which
is the directional propagation

00:37:19.820 --> 00:37:23.050
equal to 0.

00:37:23.050 --> 00:37:24.090
Any questions so far?

00:37:27.760 --> 00:37:31.930
OK, so from those
experimental results,

00:37:31.930 --> 00:37:40.900
we've found that the probability
of getting heat on the screen

00:37:40.900 --> 00:37:45.850
is proportional to
psi-1 square, if I only

00:37:45.850 --> 00:37:49.550
have the first lead there.

00:37:49.550 --> 00:37:56.430
That means the probability, p,
is proportional to psi squared.

00:37:59.330 --> 00:38:03.650
And this is actually
probably one

00:38:03.650 --> 00:38:11.420
of the most crazy results in
the physics we learned so far.

00:38:11.420 --> 00:38:15.550
In some sense, it's
kind of sad as well.

00:38:15.550 --> 00:38:18.020
Why sad?

00:38:18.020 --> 00:38:24.680
This means that, OK, I can
calculate those wave functions.

00:38:24.680 --> 00:38:28.220
And the probability
of getting an outcome

00:38:28.220 --> 00:38:32.910
at a specific position is
proportional to this wave

00:38:32.910 --> 00:38:33.685
function squared.

00:38:37.400 --> 00:38:40.990
But I feel, maybe,
demotivated, right?

00:38:40.990 --> 00:38:44.150
Because originally,
